"Neuer S., Davenport R., Freudenthal T., Wefer G., Llinás O., Rueda M.-J., Steinberg D.K., Karl D.M.","Differences in the biological carbon pump at three subtropical ocean sites",2002,"Geophysical Research Letters","29","18",,"32","1",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0242669986&partnerID=40&md5=7388252d4a4386fc0e2371277bbda8e8","Arizona State University, Department of Biology, Tempe, AZ 85287, United States; University of Bremen, Geosciences, Bremen 28344, Germany; Inst. Canario de Ciencias Marinas, Gran Canaria, Telde 35200, Spain; Virginia Institute of Marine Science, College of William and Mary, P.O. Box 1346, Virginia 23062, United States; School of Ocean/Earth Science/Tech., University of Hawaii, Honolulu, HI 96822, United States","Neuer, S., Arizona State University, Department of Biology, Tempe, AZ 85287, United States; Davenport, R., University of Bremen, Geosciences, Bremen 28344, Germany; Freudenthal, T., University of Bremen, Geosciences, Bremen 28344, Germany; Wefer, G., University of Bremen, Geosciences, Bremen 28344, Germany; Llinás, O., Inst. Canario de Ciencias Marinas, Gran Canaria, Telde 35200, Spain; Rueda, M.-J., Inst. Canario de Ciencias Marinas, Gran Canaria, Telde 35200, Spain; Steinberg, D.K., Virginia Institute of Marine Science, College of William and Mary, P.O. Box 1346, Virginia 23062, United States; Karl, D.M., School of Ocean/Earth Science/Tech., University of Hawaii, Honolulu, HI 96822, United States","We report primary production of organic matter and organic carbon removal from three subtropical open ocean time-series stations, two located in the Atlantic and one in the Pacific, to quantify the biological components of the oceanic carbon pump. We find that within subtropical gyres, export production varies considerably despite similar phytoplankton biomass and productivity. We provide evidence that the removal of organic carbon is linked to differences in nutrient input into the mixed layer, both from eddy induced mixing and dinitrogen fixation. These findings contribute to our knowledge of the spatial heterogeneity of the subtropical oceans, which make up more than 50% of all ocean area and are thought to spread in the course of CO2- induced global warming.",,"Biomass; Carbon; Global warming; Gyrators; Induction heating; Nitrogen fixation; Organic minerals; Biological carbon pump; Submarine geophysics; biological pump; gyre; nutrient availability; open ocean; organic carbon; organic matter; primary production; subtropical region",,,,,,"Altabet, M., A time-series study of the vertical structure of nitrogen and particle dynamics in the Sargasso Sea (1989) Limnol. Oceanogr, 34, pp. 1185-1201; Berger, W.H., Wefer, G., Export production: Seasonality and intermittency, and paleoceanographic implications (1990) Paleogeogr. Paleoclimatol. Paleoecol., 89, pp. 245-254; Davenport, R., Neuer, S., Helmke, P., Perez-Marrero, J., Llinás, O., Primary productivity in the northern Canary Islands region as inferred from SeaWiFS imagery Deep-Sea Res. II, , in press; Dugdale, R.C., Goering, J.J., Uptake of new and regenerated forms of nitrogen in primary productivity (1967) Limnol and Oceanogr., 12, pp. 196-206; Emerson, S., Quay, P., Karl, D., Winn, C., Tupas, L., Landry, M., Experimental determination of the organic carbon flux from open-ocean surface waters (1997) Nature, 389, pp. 951-954; Emerson, S., Mecking, S., Abell, J., The biological pump in the subtropical North Pacific Ocean: Nutrient sources, Redfield ratios and recent changes (2001) Global Biogeochemical Cycles, 15, pp. 535-554; Eppley, R.W., Peterson, B.J., Particulate organic matter flux and planktonic new production in the deep ocean (1979) Nature, 282, pp. 677-680; Falkowski, P.G., Evolution of the nitrogen cycle and its influence on the biological sequestration of CO2 in the ocean (1997) Nature, 387, pp. 272-275; Freudenthal, T., Neuer, S., Meggers, H., Davenport, R., Wefer, G., Influence of lateral particle advection and o